Frequently Asked Questions (FAQs)
1. Can international students study medicine in Poland?
Yes, international students can study medicine in Poland. Polish universities welcome students from around the world to pursue medical degrees.

2. Are medical degrees from Poland recognized internationally?
Yes, medical degrees from Polish universities are recognized internationally. They adhere to high academic standards and are accredited by relevant authorities.

3. What language is used for medical instruction in Poland?
Many medical schools in Poland offer programs in English, making them accessible to international students. Some programs may also be available in Polish.

4. Are there scholarships available for international students studying medicine in Poland?
Yes, there are scholarships and financial aid options available for international students. These may be offered by the government, universities, or other organizations.

5. What clinical opportunities are available for medical students in Poland?
Medical students in Poland have access to clinical training in hospitals, clinics, and other healthcare settings. These hands-on experiences are integral to their education.

6. Can international students work part-time while studying medicine in Poland?
Yes, international students are typically allowed to work part-time during their studies in Poland. However, there may be restrictions on the number of hours they can work.
